00:28.480 --> 00:33.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.460 --> 00:38.160
And here are your hosts.

00:43.460 --> 00:53.220
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. Philip Jose Farmer has been a mainstay
science fiction writer since 1952. He has written over 40 novels and over 80

00:53.220 --> 01:03.220
short stories focusing on a wide variety of subjects. These range from Tarzan to
the afterlife, from sex-crazed aliens to a star-faring Catholic priest. Farmer's

01:03.220 --> 01:12.080
most famous works are the Riverworld series, the World of Tears series, his
erotic fantasy novels, and the story, later a novel, The Lovers. We asked Farmer

01:12.080 --> 01:24.680
how he started writing science fiction. I started reading science fiction when I
was seven years old. I'm 63 now. And I knew I always wanted to be a writer,

01:25.260 --> 01:36.220
although I didn't do much about it for many years. The funny thing is, I
actually intended to become a mainstream writer, that is, to write stories which

01:36.220 --> 01:48.400
are not in particular genre. But I somehow or other just drifted into science
fiction and sold my first science fiction story in 1952. That was called The

01:48.400 --> 02:01.380
Lovers. It was a novelette which was published in a magazine, and it's generally
credited with breaking the taboo against the mature use of sex in a science

02:01.380 --> 02:13.600
fiction magazine. We asked Farmer if he consciously set out to break taboos by
writing The Lovers. No, I had an idea for a story, and I couldn't write it

02:13.600 --> 02:23.160
unless I broke the taboos. I didn't really consciously set out to do it because
I had the idea, and I thought it was terrific. On the other hand, I knew I was

02:23.160 --> 02:34.320
going to have a lot of trouble getting it accepted. I did. I did have a lot of
trouble. The first editor I sent it to, John Campbell, who was the editor of

02:34.320 --> 02:43.960
Astounding, was the most prestigious and the highest paying market. So
naturally, I sent it to him first. And he returned it with a comment that

02:43.960 --> 02:56.560
nauseated him. So I sent it to Horace Gold, who was editing Galaxy, which was
equally prestigious and had about the same word rates. His comments were

02:56.560 --> 03:11.000
something like John Campbell's. So then I sent it to Samuel Mines, who was
editor of a magazine called Startling Stories. And he immediately accepted it

03:11.000 --> 03:24.620
and knew it was a revolutionary breakthrough. I published it, and I was on my
way. Except that the next story I wrote was also equally revolutionary, and it

03:24.620 --> 03:36.420
took me a year before I could get anybody to accept it. Farmer is also
interested in religion in its varied forms and has used it in his works. My

03:36.420 --> 03:46.400
interest in religion has manifested itself throughout all my works. Although a
lot of people, when they say the name Farmer, immediately think of sex in a

03:46.400 --> 04:00.680
book. But the fact is I've written much more about religion than about sex. Or
sometimes both at the same time. But in some respects, sex and religion are two

04:00.680 --> 04:06.300
sides of the same coin. In certain fields of activity.

04:11.800 --> 04:20.140
But religion is only one of many themes. Farmer feels that he may have labored
in relative anonymity for years because his writings are so varied. But he has

04:20.140 --> 04:32.340
his reasons. One of the reasons I've had trouble in the early days, I think,
really becoming identified and getting a band of followers, is that I didn't

04:32.340 --> 04:46.500
beat on just one or two drums. I ranged all over the field. But I find out that
if I do a variety of stuff, I don't get tired. Each new novel is a new

04:46.500 --> 04:53.180
challenge. I'm not just working the same old theme again. Tomorrow we continue
with more on Philip Jose Farmer.

05:00.580 --> 05:08.460
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:08.460 --> 05:09.200
Odessa, Texas.

05:53.640 --> 05:57.680
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:12.720 --> 06:17.960
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:20.760 --> 06:22.340
And here are your hosts.

06:27.060 --> 06:35.520
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. We're continuing our interview with Philip
Jose Farmer. We want to explore here some background related to one of Farmer's

06:35.520 --> 06:44.220
major themes, religion. As Farmer allowed earlier, he considers himself a writer
of religious themes, even more so than a writer of sexual themes. His own

06:44.220 --> 06:53.860
religious background is quite checkered. I was sent to Sunday school when I was
very little, and I became interested in the Bible, and I read it on my own. And

06:53.860 --> 07:06.140
I even read the Book of Mormon when I was about nine years old. And I always
wrestled all my life with the problems of immortality, predestination, grace,

07:07.280 --> 07:21.240
the afterlife, and all that sort of stuff. I was raised as a Christian scientist
up until the time I was about 12. And then I was sent to a Presbyterian church

07:21.240 --> 07:24.420
where

07:24.420 --> 07:36.320
there was a conflict between Christian science and the Presbyterian idea of
predestination. And then when I was about 16, I guess I became an atheist. Now

07:36.320 --> 07:51.540
I've gone through atheism through agnosticism, and then I was converted to the
disciples of Christ. And then I backslid to go from grace, as the theological

07:51.540 --> 08:04.780
term goes. And then I lapsed back into agnosticism. And what are Farmer's
present beliefs? My present situation is that without immortality, life has no

08:04.780 --> 08:17.820
meaning. And if there's a creation, there must be a creator. But I've become
tremendously interested in what is sometimes referred to as mythicism. It isn't

08:17.820 --> 08:24.280
really like the Muslim Sufism school.

08:27.060 --> 08:39.360
than a lot of related stuff like that. You might say right now, I'm in a sort of
a limbo. Heading toward something, I don't know what. The concept of an

08:39.360 --> 08:48.420
afterlife appears repeatedly in Farmer's works. Well, if you think about it,
there could be a million different possibilities in an afterlife if there were.

08:48.420 --> 09:07.120
But one of my perhaps unstated themes is that immortality may not depend upon a
supernatural being. It's in the evolutionary drive of man for him to invent

09:07.120 --> 09:18.740
immortality himself. The drawback to that is that those people who are already
dead will remain dead, right? So that doesn't correspond to the religious idea

09:18.740 --> 09:33.920
of immortality, where everybody is raised from the first human being to the last
one. I like to do a lot of variations on that. I have a new book called The

09:33.920 --> 09:49.380
Unreasoning Mask. That's a quotation from Moby Dick. And this is concerned with
theology, afterlife, immortality. You might call it a philosophical-theological

09:49.380 --> 09:50.340
space opera.

10:06.620 --> 10:15.680
Many of Farmer's first works had the central theme of religion. The Lovers and A
Woman a Day deal with a future amalgamation of church and state called the

10:15.680 --> 10:24.220
Sturge. A popular character, Fr. John Carmody, is a planet-hopping Catholic
priest who has appeared in several short stories. We learn about his former life

10:24.220 --> 10:33.380
and conversion in the excellent novel, Night of Light. Inside Outside is a wild
tale about the afterlife and immortality. It is in fact the predecessor to the

10:33.380 --> 10:36.900
famous Riverworld series, which we will discuss in our next show.

10:44.040 --> 10:51.940
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:51.940 --> 10:52.700
Odessa, Texas.

11:35.320 --> 11:39.240
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:54.680 --> 11:59.900
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:02.620 --> 12:04.240
And here are your hosts.

12:08.700 --> 12:17.480
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. Having looked into Philip Jose Farmer's
feelings on religion and immortality, we began a look today at the Riverworld

12:17.480 --> 12:31.340
series. Farmer explains the basis of the story. It concerns the planet in which
there's a 10 million mile long river which follows the valley. And everybody

12:31.340 --> 12:45.460
that lived from about 150,000 B.C. to about 1983 A.D. was resurrected along the
banks of the river in rejuvenated form. Looks like there were 25. And the main

12:45.460 --> 12:52.100
mystery behind the whole thing was why were all these people resurrected?

12:54.040 --> 13:04.900
Who did it and how? But the Riverworld concept is so big that Farmer has
managed only to scratch the surface in the four main novels of the series. There

13:04.900 --> 13:15.040
are so many themes that I wanted to explore during the course of those four
novels, but I couldn't do it because I would have slowed the story down too

13:15.040 --> 13:25.660
much. It would have taken too many sidetracks, you might say, and I'd still be
working on that particular series. What else is left? Listen to Farmer as he

13:25.660 --> 13:35.560
gives us an inkling of what he would like to cover. I didn't go into any detail
on how you could work out viable societies with people from every place and

13:35.560 --> 13:53.260
every time. I also wanted to bring up in depth what would happen to famous
people on that planet. Like, well, there's Karl Marx, for instance. What would

13:53.260 --> 14:07.440
he think of what happened to his ideas about communism on the planet Earth after
he died? Leonardo da Vinci, his ideas about art, plus the fact that he's on a

14:07.440 --> 14:14.560
planet where there are very few pigments available, for instance, for him to
paint. What would he do there?

14:17.600 --> 14:22.180
I also wanted to bring

14:22.180 --> 14:31.620
up various figures from science and the military and philosophy and so forth,
show what they would do there. Now, one of the things about the river world was

14:31.620 --> 14:41.940
that, although you were resurrected there in a youthful body of your own, as it
was at 25 or earlier, if you died before 25,

14:44.660 --> 14:56.400
if, for instance, you were 83 when you died, and when your mind is still 83 and
you have 83 years of experience on Earth behind you, now, is your character

14:56.400 --> 15:07.740
formed? Are you going to go through perhaps a thousand years being the same
person? Or are you going to improve? And is the magic labyrinth the last word on

15:07.740 --> 15:19.540
the river world? I made a lot of people mad at me because of that last sentence
or paragraph, I should say, that I wrote in the magic labyrinth. Everything

15:19.540 --> 15:34.440
seems to have been settled. Everything has been cleared up. And then one of the
characters, the kind of minor one, Peter Jairus Frigate, he's celebrating with

15:34.440 --> 15:46.060
the others in the misty tower when he thinks he hears a footfall outside in the
hallway. Goes out, comes back, says to the others, I didn't see anyone. It must

15:46.060 --> 15:53.800
have been my imagination. A lot of readers got mad at me because they thought,
oh, no, he's going to write another one. He's leaving a loophole. Well, I am

15:53.800 --> 16:05.180
leaving a loophole, and I don't know whether I'll go through it or not. But it's
quite possible that the magic labyrinth wasn't the final one in that series

16:05.180 --> 16:17.100
before, that everything that our protagonist learned and everything that
everybody else learned is completely untrue or half the truth. So the river

16:17.100 --> 16:23.740
world novels may or may not be finished, but we do have some more sidestream
stories to anticipate. More on Farmer tomorrow.

16:31.120 --> 16:39.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:39.000 --> 16:39.760
Odessa, Texas.

17:25.040 --> 17:28.920
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:44.360 --> 17:49.700
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
