17:52.340 --> 17:54.040
And here are your hosts.

17:58.820 --> 18:08.140
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. Our show today continues the discussion
with Philip Jose Farmer. A major incident in Farmer's career began when Venus on

18:08.140 --> 18:16.620
the Half Shell, a novel written under the pseudonym Kilgore Trout, appeared in
the pages of fantasy and science fiction in late 74, early 75. Of course,

18:16.760 --> 18:24.260
Kilgore Trout is the creation of author Kurt Vonnegut, Jr. The character Trout
is an impoverished, underappreciated science fiction writer who appears in a

18:24.260 --> 18:34.240
number of Vonnegut's novels. We asked Farmer if he identifies with Kilgore
Trout. I was a fan of Vonnegut. I liked all his books, but Kilgore Trout really

18:34.240 --> 18:46.760
turned me on because his early experiences, as a matter of fact, his later ones,
too, were like a lot of my early experiences, and a lot like the experiences of

18:46.760 --> 18:56.920
many other science fiction writers back in the old days when they weren't being
paid much and science fiction was looked down upon. And we were being taken due

18:56.920 --> 19:09.780
to our inexperience by various publishers and agents. Also, I had a tough time
getting any recognition. So, I guess that's why I identified with him, plus the

19:09.780 --> 19:18.940
fact he's a great character. Vonnegut did not appreciate the reviews given Venus
on the Half Shell, either pro or con, because most of the reviewers approached

19:18.940 --> 19:27.940
the work as if Vonnegut were the author. This cost Farmer the opportunity to
write another novel under the Kilgore Trout pseudonym. I don't know what his

19:27.940 --> 19:39.620
reactions are to the novel itself, but so many people thought that he'd written
it, that he would tell you hundreds of maybe thousands of questions, and then

19:39.620 --> 19:49.020
the reviews came out. Some said Venus on the Half Shell by Kilgore Trout. It was
the worst thing he'd written, and others said it was the best thing he'd ever

19:49.020 --> 19:57.900
written. When I applied for permission to write The Son of Jimmy Valentine,
which I really would have loved to have done, because I could have had a lot of

19:57.900 --> 20:12.980
fun with it, he said no, which is his prerogative. We asked if The Son of Jimmy
Valentine was Kilgore Trout's one erotic novel. It was his, uh, not only his one

20:12.980 --> 20:22.940
and only specifically erotic book, it was also his only non-science fiction
book. Farmer obviously enjoys writing about fictional authors, who in turn write

20:22.940 --> 20:33.620
about their own fictional authors, and so on. Listen as he describes what
writing as Kilgore Trout started. In the Venus on the Half Shell, the

20:33.620 --> 20:45.280
protagonist, Simon Wagstaff, had his favorite science fiction author. Just as in
the Vonnegut books, Eliot Rosewater thought that Kilgore Trout was the

20:45.280 --> 20:53.440
greatest living writer, you know, in any field. He should have been president of
the U.S. He couldn't solve all the problems. Well, anyway, in Venus on the Half

20:53.440 --> 21:07.120
Shell, Simon Wagstaff liked to read the science fiction works of a fellow called
Jonathan Swift Somers III, and I describe his various works, or outline them,

21:07.340 --> 21:20.720
and give the title. But Jonathan Swift Somers, who's a fictional author, wrote
about a giant German shepherd police dog whose IQ had been raised to about 200

21:20.720 --> 21:34.240
in a laboratory, and he became a private detective. Now, I plan eventually
someday on writing a book by Ralph Von Valvao, this dog, under the name of Ralph

21:34.240 --> 21:47.620
Von Valvao. And then maybe I'll end the cycle by having Ralph Von Valvao write
about a human named Vonnegut, something like that, and completing it, going

21:47.620 --> 21:55.720
right back to Vonnegut again. Farmer conceded to the extended family group
called the Wold-Newton family, in which many great historical and fictional

21:55.720 --> 22:04.660
characters are descended from the Scarlet Pimpernel. Thus, Kilgore Trout is
related to Sherlock Holmes, Doc Savage, Sam Spade, and James Bond, among others.

22:04.900 --> 22:08.160
We will look into this aspect of Farmer's writing some more tomorrow.

22:15.500 --> 22:23.400
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:23.400 --> 22:24.160
Odessa, Texas.

23:07.960 --> 23:11.900
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:27.300 --> 23:32.560
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:35.240 --> 23:36.900
And here are your hosts.

23:41.540 --> 23:50.320
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. This show will conclude our interview with
Philip Jose Farmer. Yesterday we discussed Farmer's penchant for writing under

23:50.320 --> 23:54.340
pseudonyms. As it turns out, this practice has a very desirable side effect.

24:21.640 --> 24:31.800
Well, that happened to me once. I never thought it would. I thought I was immune
to such a thing. But it did. And after wrestling for two months and getting no

24:31.800 --> 24:46.900
place, I had an idea. I sat down with the typewriter and wrote a story not by
Philip Jose Farmer, but by David Copperfield, they say. I don't remember which

24:46.900 --> 25:01.640
particular nom the clue might be. The story poured out. Very good. I thought so,
anyway. When I'd completed that, the writing block was gone. See, I wasn't

25:01.640 --> 25:15.220
writing then as me, so as a Farmer, but as a Kilgore Trout. And I was in his
shoes. I had no trouble. Now, the funny thing about this is that the, it's a

25:15.220 --> 25:28.940
psychological trick that I'm conscious of, see. And yet it works. It's not like
I'm trying to trick my unconscious, but I must be doing it one way or another.

25:31.400 --> 25:41.440
Well, I don't know if anybody else has ever broken a writer's block in that
manner. But I recommend trying it. Farmer has also written several books

25:41.440 --> 25:51.660
featuring Tarzan or Tarzan-like characters. Tarzan Alive is Tarzan's biography.
The erotic novel A Feast Unknown and its clean sequels The Mad Goblin and Lord

25:51.660 --> 26:01.300
of the Trees feature thinly veiled versions of Tarzan and Doc Savage. Lord
Tiger, the Opar books, and The Adventures of the Peerless Pier also have Tarzan

26:01.300 --> 26:10.600
-like protagonists. We asked Farmer when he developed his interest in Tarzan. I
first read Tarzan when I was about seven or eight years old. And I became

26:10.600 --> 26:16.240
wrapped up in an early age with the works of such Edgar Rice Burroughs.

26:19.120 --> 26:24.340
And, but when I started college, I kind of lost interest and didn't read them
anymore.

26:30.120 --> 26:40.180
But later, Farmer picked up on Tarzan again. This time, he saw Tarzan in a
different light. I started reading books about Tarzan again. And this time,

26:41.260 --> 26:54.800
although I still kept a lot of my childhood interest in him, a sense of wonder
about him, I began seeing things in Tarzan, for instance, that I had not seen

26:54.800 --> 27:08.740
before. He was not just a child who'd been cast away and raised by great apes
and then become a creature of the jungle and then return to claim fortune. He

27:08.740 --> 27:22.940
was sort of an archetype of many, many heroes from classical myth. And now, I'm
sure that when Burroughs wrote this, he didn't know what he was doing, but he

27:22.940 --> 27:33.120
did it unconsciously. I think that the creation of Tarzan is a stroke of genius.
Burroughs is not a great writer, but he has, he has a great character, just like

27:33.120 --> 27:44.640
Acorn and Doyle. He's not a great writer, but he created a great character.
Sherlock Holmes. Philip Jose Farmer, an author with a seemingly endless supply

27:44.640 --> 27:48.820
of unique ideas, who appears just now to be gaining widespread acceptance.

27:56.340 --> 28:04.240
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

28:04.240 --> 28:05.000
Odessa, Texas.

